DOCUMENT();

############################################################
# Load Macros
############################################################
loadMacros(
  "PGstandard.pl",
  "PGML.pl",
  "AnswerFormatHelp.pl",
  "scaffold.pl",
  "parserNumberWithUnits.pl",
  "contextForm.pl",
  "contextFraction.pl",
  "randomPerson.pl",
  "parserLinearRelation.pl",
  "PGcourse.pl",
);
COMMENT('Authored in PreTeXt');
COMMENT('This problem is scaffolded with multiple parts');

############################################################
# Header
############################################################
TEXT(beginproblem());

############################################################
# PG Setup Code
############################################################
$p = randomPerson();
$b = random(12,20);
$m = random(0.04, 0.05, 0.002);
$sol = Real(($b - 1)/$m);
$distance = NumberWithUnits($sol, 'mi');
$start = NumberWithUnits($b, 'gal');
$rate = NumberWithUnits($m, 'gal/mi');
Context("Interval");
Context()->flags->set(ignoreEndpointTypes => 1);
$interval = Interval("(0,$sol]");
Context("LinearRelation")->variables->are(x => 'Real');
Context()->noreduce('(-x)-y', '(-x)+y');
$relation = Formula("$b - $m x >= 1");
Context("Fraction")->variables->are(x => 'Real');
Context()->flags->set(reduceConstants => 0, reduceFractions => 0);
Context()->noreduce('(-x)-y', '(-x)+y', '(-x)/y', 'x/(-y)');
$solleft[0] = Formula("$b - $m x - $b")->reduce;
$solright[0] = Formula("x - $b")->reduce;
$solright[0] = $solright[0]->substitute(x => Formula("1"));
$solleft[1] = Formula("-$m x")->reduce;
$solright[1] = Formula("1 - $b")->reduce;
$solleft[2] = Formula("(-$m x)/(-$m)");
$solright[2] = Formula("($solright[1])/(-$m)");

############################################################
# Body
############################################################

BEGIN_PGML
[$p] is driving on the highway, and presently has [$start] of gasoline in [$p->their] tank. [$p->Their] car, _under ideal conditions_, uses gas at a rate of [$rate]. When the tank reaches only one gallon of gas, the low gas light will turn on and [$p] will start looking for a gas station. How far will [$p->they] drive before this happens?

END_PGML

############################################################
# Scaffold
############################################################
Scaffold::Begin(numbered => 1,is_open => "correct_or_first_incorrect",can_open => always,);

############################################################
# Section
############################################################
Section::Begin("");

BEGIN_PGML
Write an inequality to represent this situation, using [`x`] to represent how many miles [$p] might drive before the low gas light turns on.

[_]{$relation}{16}

END_PGML

############################################################
# Solution
############################################################

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
This is a rate exercise, and we can use

[```
                  (\text{initial value}) \pm (\text{rate})\cdot\text{variable} \mathrel{?} (\text{final value})
                ```]

The question mark in the above is not an equal sign, because we are trying to set up an inequality. The initial value for the gas in [$p->their] tank is [`[$b]\text{,}`] [$p] is losing gas (so we will subtract, not add), the rate is [`[$m]\text{,}`] and the gas amount we are interested in reaching is [`1\text{.}`] We do not know far [$p] can drive until the gas gets that low, and we decide to use [`x`] to represent that distance. The rate of gas consumption we are using is only valid under ideal conditions. So the quantity [`[$b] - [$m] x`] will be _greater_ than or equal to the actual amount of gas left in the tank after driving [`x`] miles. And we want this to reach [`1\text{.}`] So the inequality we set up is:

[```
                  [$relation]
                ```]

END_PGML_SOLUTION

Section::End();

############################################################
# Section
############################################################
Section::Begin("");

BEGIN_PGML
Solve this inequality. At most how far will [$p] drive before the low gas light turns on?

[_]{$distance}{16}

END_PGML

############################################################
# Solution
############################################################

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION

[```
\begin{gathered}
[$solleft[0]] \geq [$solright[0]]\\
[$solleft[1]] \geq [$solright[1]]\\
[$solleft[2]] \leq [$solright[2]]\\
x \leq [$sol]
\end{gathered}
```]

So [$p] can drive at most [`[$sol]`] miles.

END_PGML_SOLUTION

Section::End();

############################################################
# Section
############################################################
Section::Begin("");

BEGIN_PGML
Use interval notation to express the number of miles [$p] might drive before the low gas light turns on.

[_]{$interval}{16}

END_PGML

############################################################
# Solution
############################################################

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
[$p] can drive at most [`[$sol]`] miles, so the right end of the interval notation for this interval will be [`[$sol]\text{,}`] with a bracket. We know [$p] has more than 1 gallon of gas when this all started, so [$p->they] can drive at least some positive number of miles. So the interval notation, accounting for the context of this exercise, is [`[$interval]\text{.}`]

END_PGML_SOLUTION

Section::End();

Scaffold::End();

############################################################
# End Problem
############################################################

ENDDOCUMENT();
